            <text type="letter" decls="#corresp1">
                <body>
                    

<opener><dateline><date>27 Aug</date></dateline>
<salute>My pr</salute></opener>
<p>I write a short letter now as I 
<lb/>may not have any time tomorrow as I 
<lb/>am going up to the line for the day.</p>
<p>I shall be <hi rend="underline">delighted</hi> to let you carry out 
<lb/>your suggestion about the family holiday. There
<lb/>is only one difficulty, that mater if she heard 
<lb/>of it might not understand. I agree with you
<lb/>in doing things in the days of our prosperity
<lb/><del>and</del>though we shall not be able to do
<lb/> them later, I know, and anything which will
        
    

    
         
        <pb n="6516" facs="#L1916_2350_img_6516"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>&#x2014; Sunday &#x2014; 
<lb/>line alteration. Tomorrow morning's won't be 
<lb/>mine so I hope you won't think it above the 
<lb/>average. Sunday morning 27<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> It looks like a wet 
<lb/>day and I am waiting for my orderly who wants to 
<lb/>go with me.</p>
 <p>Just back after rather tiring and quite exciting time 
<lb/>but I will not go with Withard again if I can help it. He 
<lb/>went against my first <gap/>by saying they never 
<lb/>shelled him, and later when we found ourselves in a trench 
<lb/>1 foot deep within full view of the enemy he seemed inca-
<lb/>table of crawling. It got rather on my nerves when I began 
<lb/>thinking of how we were to get him back. He was distinct-
<lb/>ly done up but even so he ought to have gone slower if 
<lb/>necessary. However, we got through all right after some un-
<lb/>pleasant shaves, a lot of mud a torn new mackintosh 
<lb/>and plenty of exercise.</p>
 <p>Barge was with us. Mrs Barge has a little son I
<lb/> was to be sure to tell you. If little p r had come now 
<lb/>the Ulstermen would have suffered so perhaps it is better for 
<lb/>one to come later.<p>
 <salute>Your b w</salute> <signed>WB Spender. </signed>I think it very
<lb/> good marks for writing to me again &amp; <unclear>my pr</unclear> but not if you were really tired.
        
    
         
        <pb n="6518" facs="#L1916_2350_img_6518"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>make your holiday a real one.  I am so
<lb/>glad to hear of <unclear>Mrs</unclear> Hussey's offer. It is kind
<lb/>but I think it is up to one of the others to
<lb/>take a turn. It is good of the Mother to 
<lb/>come &amp; help. I am sure she is very useful, &amp;
<lb/>I hope not too much of a tax on her. I rather
<lb/>think it may be good for her &amp; also for the 
<lb/>Pater that she shall have a little outside
<lb/> interest tho' this does not distract from her
<lb/> help. You will follow my meaning.</p> 
<p>I find Withard <add>GS02</add> of the XV Corps was a 
<lb/>contemporary of Edmund's at Radley I was 
<lb/>with him today &amp; go up I hope with him
<lb/> tomorrow. It is curious that my <unclear>gazette</unclear> is<pb/>
        
    
         
        <pb n="6519" facs="#L1916_2350_img_6519"/>
        
        
           
            <lb/>so long in coming. I wonder if there is a hitch.
<lb/>I wish they would make Rex a Captain. From 
<lb/>his last letter I judge that he is settling in a bit
<lb/>now.</p>
<p>I got off a letter to Mater really a good
<lb/> b w, &amp; rather scolded her for her scolding. I hope
<lb/>you will see her when as soon as she returns from the 
<lb/><unclear>Rundle's</unclear> &amp; invite yourself to dinner. If you could
<lb/>stop there a few days before you settle into 
<lb/>your new home it would be nice but don't
<lb/> tire yourself with her deafness. It will mean 
<lb/>many extravagant taxies to the Palace ahem!</p>
<p>Did I tell you that K's correction to my draft 
<lb/>was so bad that I had to correct his correction 
<lb/>quite a lot. Today mine was passed with only one
        
    
                </body>
